# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balle-à-la-main
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The town was fought over during both World Wars, suffering significant damage, and was repeatedly occupied by both sides.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The 1918 Battle of Amiens was the opening phase of the Hundred Days Offensive which directly led to the Armistice with Germany.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Royal Air Force heavily bombed the town during the Second World War.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In the aftermath, the city was rebuilt according to Pierre Dufau's plans with wider streets to ease traffic congestion.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] These newer structures were primarily built of brick, concrete and white stone with slate roofs.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The architect Auguste Perret designed the Gare d'Amiens train station and nearby Tour Perret.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens has an important historical and cultural heritage, on which a significant amount of tourism is based.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Apart from the cathedral, there are the hortillonnages, the Jules Verne House, the Tour Perret, the Musée de Picardie, the zoo, and the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] A total of 60 monuments are listed in the inventory of monuments historiques, over 1600 places and monuments listed in the general inventory of cultural heritage, and 187 objects listed in the inventory of monuments historiques.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] During December, the town hosts the largest Christmas market in northern France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The first known settlement at this location was **Samarobriva** ("Somme bridge"), the central settlement of the Ambiani tribe, one of the principal tribes of Gaul.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Romans named the town Ambianum, meaning settlement of the Ambiani people.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens was part of Francia starting from the 5th century.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Normans sacked the city in 859 and again in 882.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 1113, the city was recognized by King Louis VI of France, and in 1185 it was linked to the Crown of France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 1597, Spanish soldiers held the city during the six-month Siege of Amiens, before Henry IV regained control.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] During the 18th and 19th century, the textile tradition of Amiens became famous for its velours.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] As a result of the French Revolution, the provinces of France were dismantled and the territory was organised into departments.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Much of Picardy became the newly created department of Somme with Amiens as the departmental capital.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] During the industrial revolution, the city walls were demolished, opening up space for large boulevards around the town center.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Henriville neighborhood in the south of the city was developed around this time.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 1848, the first railway arrived in Amiens, linking the city to Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] During the 1870 Battle of Amiens, the city was occupied by invading Prussian forces.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The town was fought over during both the First and Second World Wars, suffering significant damage and being occupied several times by both sides.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The 1918 Battle of Amiens was the opening phase of the Hundred Days Offensive which led directly to the Armistice with Germany that ended the war.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In June 1944 following D-Day, Amiens was heavily bombed by the Royal Air Force.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The town was liberated by British forces on 31 August.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The city was rebuilt according to Pierre Dufau's plans with a focus on widening the streets to ease traffic congestion.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens, once regional prefecture of the former Picardy Region, is the prefecture of the Somme department, one of the three departments (with Oise and Aisne) in the region.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Located in the Paris Basin, the city benefits from a privileged geographical position, with close proximity to Paris, Lille, Rouen, London and Brussels.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] At the crossroads of major European routes of travel (A1, A16 and A29), the city is also at the heart of a major rail star.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] As the crow flies, the city is 115 kilometres (71 mi) north of Paris, 97 kilometres (60 mi) south-west of Lille, 100 kilometres (62 mi) north-east of Rouen, 162 kilometres (101 mi) east-north-east of Le Havre and 144 kilometres (89 mi) north-west of Reims.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] At the regional level, Amiens is located 53 kilometres (33 mi) north of Beauvais, 71 kilometres (44 mi) west of Saint-Quentin, 66 kilometres (41 mi) from Compiègne and 102 kilometres (63 mi) from Laon.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In area, Amiens is the third-largest settlement in the Somme, after Crécy-en-Ponthieu and Hornoy-le-Bourg.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The area of the commune is 4,946 hectares (12,220 acres); the altitude varies between 14 and 106 metres (46 and 348 ft).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The main stem of the River Somme passes through Amiens and is generally benign, except during exceptional floods that can last up to several weeks (such as in spring 2001).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It is also, on its southeastern outskirts, close to Camon and Longueau, the confluence with its main tributary on the left bank (to the south), and the Avre.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The city developed in a natural narrowing of the river due to the advance of the rim of the Picard plateau in Saint-Pierre (ford crossing).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Amiens citadel is built on this limestone butte of the Picard plateau and *Rue Saint-Pierre* is a slightly inclined path to leave the city from the north.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] At this narrowing, a network of narrow canals led to the construction of bridges and buildings including textile mills in the Middle Ages.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The marshes of the old bed of the river Somme was used to dig peat.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Farmers maintained rieux, canals and ditches by cleaning out the silt and used it to append to their vegetable garden plot.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] During the 20th century maintenance of the canals was stopped and gardens were gradually left to lie fallow or sold to private individuals who created pleasure gardens accessible by boat.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The hydrographic network has always been an important city-operated asset.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The river helped shape the identity of the landscape, urban and economic territory.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It is around the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods that border the River Somme, as well as most of the administrative and civil area of the current city center which the city has developed since antiquity.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Canal de la Somme dates from the beginning of the 19th century and the bridge at the foot of the citadel was built after World War II.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens has the typical oceanic climate of the north of France, with relatively mild winters, cool summers, and rainfall well distributed throughout the year.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens is a hub between the Île de France and the rest of northern France; Normandy and Benelux; and France and Great Britain.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens is not directly on principal European road and rail arteries, such as the A1 motorway and the Paris-Lille TGV train line, at present.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] However, due to its position halfway between the urban areas of Lille and Paris, Amiens has good conditions for service and accessibility, including motorways (at the junction of the A16 and A29).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens station is served by regional train services to destinations that include Rouen, Calais, Lille, Reims, Compiègne and Paris-Nord.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Saint-Roch (Somme) station in the western part of the city is served by local trains towards Rouen and Abbeville.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] A regular bus route with the TGV Haute-Picardie station also provides access to the Charles-de-Gaulle Airport station.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] On the horizon of 2025, the Roissy–Picardie Link will put Amiens 55 minutes from Paris Charles-de-Gaulle Airport and its TGV station.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Since antiquity, Amiens has been a crossroads of important routes.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The contemporary city is served by the A16 and A29 autoroutes.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Jules Verne Viaduct, 943 metres (3,094 ft) long, crosses the River Somme to the east of the city and allows circumvention of the city by motorway-type roads.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The A16 and A29 autoroutes, the RN1 and the RN25 form a bypass-type motorway around the city that the population has called the *Rocade d'Amiens* or Amiens ring road.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] According to the urban transport plan (PDU) approved 19 December 2013 for the period 2013–2023 parking supply is considered abundant in Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Although important, demand for parking is less than what is available (capacity reserves are still 20% minimum: If the road is sometimes saturated, the occupancy rate of the underground parking remains globally less than 100%).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 2013, the city counted approximately 70,000 public parking spaces, including 8,400 in the city center and in its immediate vicinity, where 70% of places are paid.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] As of 2007, a residential parking system has been deployed in Saint-Anne ward to cope with congestion in the streets caused by SNCF railway station users.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] During the campaign for the municipal election of 2008, parking was one of the important topics of debate.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] A year after the change of majority, the Gilles Demailly team launched a consultation with the population.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] From 2011, residential parking was extended to the Gare-La-Vallée and Riolan neighborhoods, then in 2012 to the Noyon neighborhood and the area east of the Riolan sector.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 2014, 2,600 parking spaces were affected by this system which allowed city residents more parking near their homes in order to promote a better rotation of vehicles in the streets and reduce permanent occupation of public space by the cars cluttering the highway.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens was once served by two tram lines with a combined length of 10.7 kilometres (6.6 mi), opened in 1887.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] They intersected at *Place Gambetta*, one linking La Madeleine Cemetery, the Church of Saint-Acheul, Cagnard bridge, *Rue de Noyon* and *Rue Jules-Barni*; the other from the Church of Saint-Pierre at the racecourse, by the streets of Saint-Leu, Frédéric-Petit and Colbert.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Electrified in 1899, the network grew to seven lines totaling 19 kilometres (12 mi) in 1906.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] From 1932, Longueau was linked to Amiens by a bus service.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] German bombing in 1940 destroyed most of the city center and hit the Jules-Ferry Road tram depot, totally destroying the tram fleet.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] A few old Parisian buses were also used in an extremely reduced service.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] These buses as well as the surviving bus were then converted to city gas and equipped with tanks on the roof covered by a huge white dome.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] This service continued until approximately 1946.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] There were only two urban lines: An east–west line (Saint-Acheul – Montieres) and a northeast–southwest line (Beauville – road to Rouen).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It was decided after the war to serve the city by a trolleybus with one route to Longueau.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] This was only in part realized, serving Saint-Acheul, Rouen, La Madeleine and Saint-Pierre.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 1964, trolleybuses were abandoned and the bus became ubiquitous in Amiens transportation.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The current public transport network consists of a bus network managed by the Ametis mixed economy company, whose network covers Amiens Métropole, the agglomeration of Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The establishment of dedicated bus lanes began in 2006.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Former Mayor Gilles de Robien had envisioned the creation of a tram, but the choice of dedicated bus lanes had been preferred for reasons of cost and patronage.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] His successor, Mayor Gilles Demailly, had been considering the development of a TSCP in the metropolitan area.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] As a result of numerous studies and conferences, elected representatives voted for the creation of a tram at the municipal Council of 15 November 2012.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The project had been endorsed by the Communauté d'agglomération Amiens Métropole on 18 December 2012 and the commissioning of a first north–south tram route was scheduled for 2018/2019.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Improvement of public transit would then be only by that of the bus network.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Indeed, in December of the same year, the Community Council approved funding for a study (the sixth in 20 years) relating to the establishment of a rapid transit bus network (BHNS), which should enter into service in March 2019, and whose vehicles could be electric.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens has developed two bike services: Buscyclette and Velam.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 2012, Amiens Métropole had 100 kilometres (62 mi) of routes for cyclists.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Despite the development of a bicycle plan in 1997 which was planning the development of 500 kilometres (310 mi) of equipped cycleways, the network of the territory in terms of paths is still incomplete.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The blueprint of the bicycle facilities of the agglomeration (SDAC) provides, over a period of 10 years (2014–2024), for 188 kilometres (117 mi) of cycle routes and equips 490 sites for the parking of bikes.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] This plan also includes the deployment of parking facilities over the entire territory of the city, close to the facilities frequented by bikers, as well as cyclist right-turns at traffic lights or even the maintenance of existing facilities.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Connections from these two stations include to Lille via Arras and Douai, to Boulogne via Abbeville, to Paris-Nord via Creil or Compiègne, to Reims via Tergnier, and to Rouen.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Many regional and extra regional links (Normandie, Grand Est and Île-de-France) pass through Amiens, especially by TER Hauts-de-France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] A station located 45 kilometres (28 mi) from Amiens, the Haute-Picardie TGV station, allows access to the TGV network.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Its isolated character earned it the name of *gare des betteraves*, or *gare betteraves*, at the time of its construction.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In addition to Amiens – Glisy Aerodrome, bordering the town's eastern edge 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) from the center, there are several airports nearby.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Somme canal runs through the town to the English Channel.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] This canal is linked to the Canal du Nord (Paris to Lille metropolitan area).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens comprises a number of neighborhoods (French: *quartiers*) with their own characteristics, including Saint-Leu, St-Maurice, Henriville, and Saint-Acheul.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] St-Leu forms part of Amiens, north of the city center.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It has many older wooden and brick houses and several canals.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] At the foot of the cathedral, traversed by canals, this picturesque area was largely rehabilitated during the 1990s.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It extends to the Somme canal, located more to the north, at the foot of the Coteau Saint-Pierre on which the fortress of Jean Errard, called *Citadelle*, was built.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Historically, it was the poor neighborhood of the city, where butchers, tanners and dyers gathered.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens University's Faculty of Sciences, present since the 1960s, has been renovated and expanded on occasion.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Faculty of Law and Economics has also been transferred since the mid-1990s from the campus (offset to the south of the city) to its new location at the foot of the cathedral.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The open-air parking it replaces was a "gap" in the landscape dating from World War II.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Nonetheless, it allowed an unobstructed view of the cathedral.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Most of the buildings have been renovated and transformed into housing much of which is for students.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The area became the heart of the Amiens people's evenings, with many establishments (bars, restaurants, etc.) on *Place du Don* and *Quai Bélu*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The church is found at *Rue Saint-Leu*, located just between the Faculty of Science and Law-Economy (UPJV).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Two theatres were established in the neighborhood, that of the Chés Cabotans (puppet shows in the Picard language) and the *Maison du Théâtre* at the foot of the Saint-Leu Church.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] There is also *La Lune des Pirates*, a concert hall.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Located to the west of the Citadelle, and east of the La Madeleine Cemetery, this very old working-class neighborhood of Amiens acted as an industrial center in the 18th century.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It is currently undergoing significant housing renovation and development.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Bordered by the Canal de la Somme, it offers a stopover for leisure boats, which must go through a lock.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The walls of the city's former dye factory are now those of the École supérieure d'art et de design d'Amiens (ESAD) as well as those of the Faculty of Arts.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The École supérieure d'ingénieurs en électronique et électrotechnique (ESIEE) is in the same neighborhood.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Jardin des plantes, known as the *Jardin du Roy* within the city, is also located in this neighborhood.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Henriville neighborhood was mostly built during the 19th century after the demolition of the city wall.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It lies at the south of the town center.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It has numerous bourgeois houses and townhouses, predominantly in brick, blending architectural styles of the period, including neoclassical, troubadour and neo-Gothic.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] There are also private mansions, such as the Acloque mansion and the house of Jules Verne.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Saint-Acheul neighborhood (IPA: [sɛ̃t‿aʃœl]) existed before Amiens' inception, as people have lived there since prehistoric times.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] This is where archaeological excavations in the nineteenth century discovered prehistoric tool sets typical of the "Acheulean" prehistorical era, named after this neighborhood (also spelled Acheulian, pronounced [aʃœljɑ̃]).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Thr archaeological garden there is open to the public.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Not to be confused with the commune of Saint-Acheul situated 37 km (23 mi) to the north, the Saint-Acheul neighborhood is the site of a military cemetery from the First World War (1914–1918).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It also contains the Church of Saint-Acheul, the Jesuit former Saint-Acheul College and the former normal school (teacher-training college), which became the Lycée Robert-de-Luzarches.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] A number of famous people are buried in the former Saint-Acheul cemetery, such as the creator of *Bécassine*, J.P.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Part of the neighborhood includes a so-called English neighborhood, with typical English-style houses.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] At the foot of this area lie the *hortillonnages*, a marshy area criss-crossed by canals.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] These areas experience a lot of social troubles and have regularly been the place for riots.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The cost of the latest vandalism to occur in the north of Amiens would amount, according to Gilles Demailly, to between four and six million euros.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] These extremely violent riots caused sixteen police officers to be injured.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] An extensive programme of redevelopment of these neighborhoods began recently, with demolition of HLM tower blocks and new infrastructure having been built, especially for schools.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 2009, the public transport network of the Amiens agglomeration was significantly modified.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In 2017, the total number of dwellings in the municipality was 73,541, while it was 63,178 in 1999.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Among this housing, 88.7% were primary residences, 2.1% of secondary residences and 9.2% vacant housing.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] These dwellings were 35.6% of houses and 63.4% of apartments.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The proportion of principal residences, which were the properties of occupants, was 31.9%, down from 2007 (34.4%).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The share of empty rented HLM homes (social housing) was up: 29.8% against 29.4% in 2007, their number increased from 18,268 to 19,431.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] However, this percentage remains much greater than the rate of 20% required by the Law on Solidarity and Urban Renewal (SRU) for cities and agglomerations of more than 50,000 inhabitants.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The identity of the city is strongly marked by the specificity of its housing stock, consisting in a large proportion of detached houses, semi-detached, single or bourgeois: the *amiénoises*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] These traditional houses in the suburbs, in brick, were intrinsically linked to the expansion of the city during and after the Industrial Revolution.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The *amiénoise simple* includes a window on the ground floor and floors for attic and basement.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] It is built on a plot of a few metres wide but is very deep, and includes a garden, forming hearts with green islets and sparse areas.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The *amiénoise double* has two windows at each level.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The *grandes amiénoises* and townhouses rise to at least two floors with large rooms.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] They can have a gate opening onto a paved courtyard.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The official buildings or mansions regularly use brick façades on a sandstone base, decorated by stone window and door frames.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Chanoines neighborhood has stone façades exclusively.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] In historic areas such as the Saint-Leu neighborhood, façades widely use wood, half-timbered or siding, and wattle and daub.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The toponym is derived from the name of the local Gallic people, the Ambiani, which in the 4th century, replaced the old name of the town Samarobriva (the bridge on the Samara – Somme).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens then became the episcopal headquarters.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Amiens municipal council has 55 elected members.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] On 4 April 2014, Brigitte Fouré (IDU (NC)) succeeded Gilles Demailly (PS) as mayor of Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Her list was elected in the second round on 30 March 2014 with 50.39% of the votes.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens is a city marked by a strong judicial tradition, with the historical presence of its Court of Appeal, the Cour d'appel d'Amiens, as well as all courts of first and second degree of judicial order.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] The Court of Appeal of Amiens has jurisdiction over the three departments of Picardy, with nine high courts.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p01] Amiens also has friendly relations with Mianyang in China and Amiens in Australia.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The inhabitants of Amiens are called the *Amiénois* and their blason populaire is *Chés maqueux d'gueugues* (the eaters of nuts).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The population of Amiens has risen sharply since the mid-19th century: Its population doubled between 1850 and 1960, from 50,000 to 100,000 inhabitants, i.e. a gain of 50,000 people over this period of 110 years, and gaining about 30,000 others since (over 50 years only this time).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Amiens is distinguished by the youthfulness of its population.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Notably the age group 15-24 is much larger (21.2%) than the average of the Somme department (13.2%).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Educational institutions of the city fall under the supervision of the Academy of Amiens which develops curriculum according to the Inspection académique la Somme.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] On 1 September 2010, 10,658 children were enrolled in the Amiens public schools: 4,341 in nursery school and 6,317 in elementary school.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2011, the Amiens agglomeration included 46 nursery schools, six elementary schools and 54 primary schools including eleven private.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It had nine public colleges and six private colleges.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens metropole welcomes one of the largest student populations in France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2013, the city had 26,000 students (3,300 in short-term) and 800 researchers who are divided into some 40 institutions of higher education, 32 laboratories, and 10 units associated with the National Scientific Research Centre or the French Institute of Health and Medical Research.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Since 2014, the four sites have been gradually gathered on the current site of the South Hospital, with the exception of the long stay units for the elderly remaining in the Saint-Victor Centre.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] This merger will be completed in 2016 and allow the CHU of Amiens to increase its national and inter-regional dimension.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] This group represents the largest hospital construction of France and one of the most important in Europe with more than €630 million for work and equipment.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] At the end of the work, the total space of the CHU of Amiens will be 172,000 square metres (1,850,000 sq ft).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It will total three blocks of hospitals with 400 beds each.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The CHU of Amiens is the largest employer in the Picardy region.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] At the end of the merger, there will be 6,700 employees, 1,300 students of the health professions, and 1,250 consultants who will go there each day.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In order to maintain the availability of health units to the north of the city, a health center will open its doors in the first quarter of 2016, at the crossroads of the *Avenue de l'Europe* and the *Rue Maurice-Ravel*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] This health space of 1,200 square metres (13,000 sq ft) will host general practitioners and specialists of the CHU such as: cardiologist, a service of gynaecology-obstetrics, psychologists, dentist, and masseurs-physiotherapists.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] There is a promise of a permanence of care, 7 days a week and 24 hours a day.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Alongside the CHU, there are three private clinics, resulting from the consolidation of old clinics in the city.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] These care and hospitalisation institutions for medical, surgical, and obstetrics came together to create a private hospital center in the Vallée des Vignes neighborhood, south of the city.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The CHU of Amiens figured in 11th place in the *2013 awards of the hospitals and clinics* of the magazine *Le Point*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In this ranking, the CHU stands out for ankle surgery (3rd), hip prosthesis (5th), foot surgery (7th) and paediatrics (14th).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In this same classification, the Victor Palmer Health Group, equipped with a solid "mother-to-child hub", gained a 5th place in the table for the gynaecological clinics and an 8th place for breast cancers.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2005, the CHU of Amiens became of international renown thanks to Professor Bernard Devauchelle, a native of the city, where his team performed the first partial face transplant in the world.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Thanks to a large proportion of youth in its population and the dynamism and the success of its sports clubs, Amiens has been awarded the title of "Sportiest city of France" by the *L'Équipe* newspaper in 1999.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The city had already won the title in 1969.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2013, Amiens Métropole had nearly 300 sports associations and Sports Recreation: approximately 150 associations are grouped within the Office of Amiens Metropole Sports and 150 others are referenced without being adherents.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] According to this same Office for Sports, Amiens has 25,000 members of sports clubs, excluding school and university members.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens Spartiates, operating in the top-level Ligue Élite de Football Américain, have been champions of France in 2004, 2010 and 2012.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Created in 1987, the club has more than 400 licensees.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Compagnie d'Arc d'Amiens is an archery club founded on 14 November 1803.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] AUC Athlétisme is a multidisciplinary athletic club which particularly developed Stella Akakpo, specialist of the sprint and the relay.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Bertrand Moulinet specialist of the 20 km and 50 km walk.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The AUC Badminton (Amiens University Badminton Club) was founded in 1986.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Labeled "French school of badminton" by the French Badminton Federation, the club had 205 members in 2014.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The city hosted the French National Badminton Championships in 2011.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Each 15 August at the Parc de la Hotoie, Amiens receives the final stages of Ballon au poing.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Circle of Fencing of Amiens Métropole is one of the oldest French clubs.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It was succeeded in the Hall of arms of Amiens opened in 1886.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The circle has approximately 150 members and remains a major club of French fencing with many qualifications and results at the French Fencing Championships.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The club held the Elite French Championships in 2001 and 2011.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The team was finalist of the Coupe de France in 2001 and reached semifinals in 1930 and 2008, and played top-division Ligue 1 last time in 2020.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Its associated women's team is CS Amiens Club.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Before the 2012–2013 season, the team was known under the name of CS Amiens Montieres Etouvie.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] AC Amiens is the second biggest club in the city, currently playing in semi-professional Championnat National level.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Golf Club D'amiens was founded in 1924.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The men's team plays in D1, women team in D2.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens Picardie Hand (APH), currently playing in National 2 (D4).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The club, a result of the merger of several Amiens clubs, was created in 1991.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Gothiques d'Amiens, currently playing in Ligue Magnus (D1), were champions of France in 1999 and 2004, and runners-up in France for 1989, 1997, 1998, 2003 and 2006.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The team plays at the Coliséum on the largest area of permanent ice in France (3800 seats).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Amiens hosted Division I of the 2006 Ice Hockey World Championships.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Amiens won the Championship of France in 6/6, 10 times.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Écureuils d'Amiens, Elite League (D1), were the runners-up of France in 2010, finalists of the Coupe de France in 2007 and finalists of the European Cup of clubs in 2008.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Sport Nautique d'Amiens (SNA) was founded in 1866.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Located on the edge of the Parc Saint-Pierre, it is labeled "French rowing school 3 stars" by the French Federation of rowing.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] With 465 members in 2013, the club currently competes in the 2nd division.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Rugby Club Amiénois (RCA) was founded in 1900.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The men's first team plays in Fédérale 3.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens Métropole swim team, is that of Jérémy Stravius, who was a triple world champion of swimming and Olympic champion in the 4 × 100 m relay.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens Sport Table Tennis (ASTT) was founded in 1945.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It was twice crowned champion of France in 1968 and 1969.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The men's first team also won the Coupe de France in 1966 and 1967.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Amiens Athletic Club (AAC) was founded in 1904.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It is one of the 10 biggest clubs in France with almost 1,000 members in 2013.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens Longueau Métropole Volley-Ball (ALMVB) including women's first team plays in Women's Elite Division (D2) and the Amiens Métropole Volley-Ball (AMVB).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The men's first team plays in Nationale 1 (D3).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Amiens hosted the finish of Stage 8 of the 2018 Tour de France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] On 29 April 2006, Amiens hosted the French Federation of ice hockey created during the World Cup of Ice Hockey of Group B (antechamber of the world elite) organised in Amiens at the same time.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It is now installed at Issy-les-Moulineaux.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Each 15 August at the *Parc de la Hotoie*, the city receives the final stages of the Picardy sports and in particular those of the most emblematic, traditional Picard sport: The Ballon au poing.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] This Picard game is played by teams of six.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] To be able to hit the ball, players surround their hand and their wrist with a strip of canvas or leather.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] From August 29 to September 1, 2012, the Compagnie d'Arc d'Amiens organizes the French FITA Archery Championships at the Hippodrome du petit Saint-Jean.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Free newspapers *Metro* and *20 minutes* are distributed in the city, including in Amiens railway station.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Since 7 February 1996, the Communauté d'agglomération Amiens Métropole distributes a free weekly local newspaper: JDA (*Journal des Amiénois*).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] This publication, which appears every Wednesday, is distributed to all homes in the metropolitan area and is made available in public places (taken at about 95,000 copies) as well as on the internet site of the city in its digital version.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Over time, the journal has evolved through various forms.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Carried out by the Directorate of communication of Amiens Métropole, the latest form dates to 16 January 2015.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In addition to the JDA which is attached to information on the whole of the territory of Amiens Métropole, the city has also had monthly publications specific to the city, which no longer exist today: *Amiensville* then *Amiens Forum* (from April 2009 to June 2014).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The people of Amiens have other sources of information on their territory, such as the monthly publication of the Regional Council of Picardy, *Agir en Picardie*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Departmental Council of the Somme also sees its magazine distributed each month to the samariens homes, *Vivre en Somme*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Since 2006, the regional tourism committee of Picardy publishes *Esprit de Picardie*, a travel magazine on the Picardy region, every six months.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Most of the national radio stations broadcast their programs in the Amiens area and can be added to France Bleu Picardie (100.2 MHz) and local stations Radio Campus Amiens (87.7 MHz) and Radio Galaxie programme Évasion (97.7 MHz).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] As of 1 March 2015, the CSA has not selected Amiens for broadcast or experimentation of this broadcasting standard.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Zen Sōtō Zen centre affiliated with the international Zen Association, on *Rue Vulfran Warmé*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The synagogue in Amiens is located at 12 *Rue du Port d'Amont*, near Pont-Beauville.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has a place of worship on the Doullens road.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The city of Amiens has the largest Muslim community of Picardy and one of the largest in the north of France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Places of worship are evolving, several mosques are in a phase of expansion or relocation.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Several independent prayer rooms are present in the urban community.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] On the other hand, Muslim committees and associations exist in the image of the Islamic Cultural Centre of Amiens in the *Rue de Savoie*, the Muslim Cultural Freedom Association – Institute of Enlightenment and also the Association of residents of the home at 21 *Route d'Allonville*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Protestant Church of Amiens, *Rue Saint-Jacques*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] As both an industrial hub and a services center, Amiens enjoys a large pool of workers with a labor pool of over 350,000 inhabitants and numerous professional training courses.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The magazine *L'Entreprise* elected Amiens "Most attractive city of France" for businesses, in 2009 and 2007, for the category less than 200,000 inhabitants.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The strengths of the city include a developed real estate business and taxation around the average for French cities.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In addition, its geographical position in the center of the triangle "Paris – London – Brussels", is between three major European cities.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The magazine *Challenges* has also designated Amiens as "Best managed city of France", for the category large cities with more than 100,000 inhabitants, in 2011, 2010 and 2008.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2010, the median taxable household income was €22,539, which placed Amiens at 177th place among the 31,525 communes with more than 39 households in metropolitan France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2017, the proportion of taxable households was 45%.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2017, the population aged 15 to 64 years amounted to 91,555 persons, among which there were 64.5% of assets including 51.4% having a job and 13.1% of unemployed.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] There were 78,284 jobs in the employment area, against 80,908 in 2007.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The number of assets employed and residing in the area of employment being 47,588.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The concentration of jobs indicator is 164.5%, which means that the employment area offers three jobs for every two active inhabitants.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Agriculture has very little representation among Amiens jobs with only 0.2%, just as the construction sector which represents 4.3% of jobs.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Unlike these two sectors whose share is below the national average, the tertiary sector (trade, transport, services) represents a significant part of the Amiens workforce, 42.3%.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Public services (public administration, education, health, social work) accounts for 42.7%.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company announced more than 400 job cuts in May 2008 at the Amiens plant, which has had 1,450 employees; in March 2009, the management announced new collective redundancies of a thousand jobs.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] On 31 December 2015, at Amiens, there were 10,436 businesses: 51 in agriculture, forestry and fisheries, 394 in industry, 685 in construction, 7,110 in trade, transportation and various services and 2,196 were related to the administrative sector.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2018, 1,505 companies had been recorded as being established in Amiens, including 1,206 companies owned by sole proprietors.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Philatelic publishers Yvert et Tellier (catalogues of quotes) and *l'Écho de la timbrologie* (magazine) have their management in Amiens, even if they have more of their services in the Paris region.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Gueudet Group, one of the largest car dealers in France, was established at Amiens in 1918.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The old textile tradition of the city remains with the factory of Lee Cooper France (122 employees).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Since the end of World War II, much of the city's economy was tied to automotive equipment with companies such as Valeo, Goodyear and Sumitomo-Dunlop tires.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] In 2003, the American Goodyear company bought Dunlop.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] These two companies suffered financially through late 2007 and early 2008, and in response, the American Goodyear company headquarters in the United States offered workers a change to their working hours and the number of posts, which a high percentage of staff refused.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Procter & Gamble, settled in Amiens in 1964 to produce soap, and inaugurated its new detergents unit in 1966.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Established on over more than 45 hectares (110 acres), it is one of the largest factories in the world for laundry cleaning products (Ariel, Dash, Bonux, Gama) and for domestic cleaning products (Mr.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] More than 85% of its production is intended for export.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Amiens plant employs approximately 930 people.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Since the mid-1990s, the city has tried to convert the economy towards the internet and telephony industries.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Many call centres (Intracall center, Coriolis France, Médiamétrie) have opened mainly within the city, region or state.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] The Unilog (now Logica) computer service company has installed a service center in Amiens (the CSA).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] Amiens is the seat of the Regional Chamber of commerce and industry of Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It is also the seat of the Chamber of commerce and industry of Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p02] It manages the Amiens - Glisy Aerodrome.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The strategic position of Amiens makes it an attractive destination for a weekend or a few days, from Paris, Lille or Brussels.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Amiens also benefits from the proximity of the Baie de Somme, a tourist hotspot registered at the Club des plus belles baies du monde and labelled Great Site of France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Amiens has the label of Towns and Lands of Art and History since 1992.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Within this framework, the host of the heritage organises guided tours on themes intended for an audience of adults and children, with educational workshops.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] A signposted circuit allows an independent tour of the town, with information panels offering comment on places and notable buildings.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Amiens has an important historical and cultural heritage, and an accessible and varied natural heritage, on which tourism is based.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The main attractions are the cathedral, which is included in the world heritage of UNESCO, the *hortillonnages*, Jules Verne House, the Tour Perret, the Musée de Picardie, the zoo, and the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The information given below is relative only to a brief selection.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The city is famous for its Notre-Dame Cathedral, masterpiece of Gothic art and one of the largest cathedrals in the world by its interior volume (200,000 m3 (7,100,000 cu ft)).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The largest religious and medieval building of France, its interior could twice hold Notre-Dame de Paris.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The cathedral measures 145 metres (476 ft) long and its spire rises 112 metres (367 ft) high.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The vaults of the central nave, finished in 1247, are 42.3 metres (139 ft), close to the maximum limit for this architecture.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Dating back to the 13th century, its construction is due to the wealth of the city in the Middle Ages and to the fire of the Romanesque cathedral which stood previously.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Three architects, including Robert of Luzarches succeeded to complete the construction.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Amiens Cathedral is notable for the coherence of its plan, the beauty of its three-tier interior elevation, the particularly fine display of sculptures on the principal façade and in the south transept, and inlays of its floor.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Regarded as the archetype of the classic Gothic style, the cathedral also presents some elements of the radiant Gothic style and flamboyant Gothic.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The speed of construction, barely 70 years for the shell (1220 to 1269), explains this remarkable homogeneity of style.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Its façade is decorated with more than 3,000 statues, gargoyles and chimeras.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Registered since 1981 as a World Heritage Site of UNESCO, it is a "masterpiece of world heritage".
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] For a second time in 1998, it is a monumental step on the Camino de Santiago.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Despite the two World Wars of the 20th century, which severely affected the city, it managed to stay intact.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] A show of the reproduction of the original polychromy of façades, discovered as a result of recent laser cleaning, is given annually for free in December and during the summer period.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The show is a projection on the façade of slides in color.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The zodiac is a set of reliefs on the foundations of the western façade formed series of quatrefoil medallions, carved in a representative agrarian calendar and the signs of the zodiac.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The statue of the weeping Angel that is on a tomb carved by Nicolas Blasset, and the reliefs evoking Saint-Firmin and St.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] John the Baptist, are some of the well-known works of the cathedral.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] At ground level lies the intact labyrinth of 234 metres (768 ft) long.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] On the north side of the cathedral is the former Palace of the Bishop of Amiens, occupied by the École supérieure de commerce in Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The origin of the Belfry of Amiens dates back to the establishment of the commune of Amiens by Louis VI.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] It is mentioned for the first time in an arbitral award issued by the chapter of Amiens in 1244.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Symbolizing the independence of the commune, it was formerly used for meetings of the notables of the city and then as archive rooms, weapons store and prison.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] A spotter nearby monitored arrivals and warned the population of the external dangers.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] During the Middle Ages, the building was repeatedly engulfed by fire.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The belfry is composed of a base in white cut stone, built in the 15th century between 1406 and 1410, a stone superstructure bell tower built from 1749 with Baroque volutes at its base, and a dome covered with slate and then the renowned arrow weather vane.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] At the time, a huge 11-ton bell was installed inside, it was later destroyed along with the dome, whose copper component melted, in the bombardment and fire of the city on 19 May 1940.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Abandoned and devoid of a roof since World War II, the monument was fully restored between February 1989 and July 1990.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Located on the *Place au Fil*, the old central square of the city before the arrival of the railway and the rise of the *Rue des Trois Calloux*, the belfry is adjacent to *Les Halles* and the back of the *Hôtel de Ville* (city hall).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] At a height of 52 metres (171 ft), it rings every hour of the day.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Since July 2005, the belfry of Amiens is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, as part of a set of 56 Belfries of Belgium and France which were inscribed because of their architecture and their importance in the rise of municipal power in Northern France and Belgium.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The belfry is also recorded in the inventory of Historic Monuments.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] In 1845, the traditional fair of Saint-Jean, formerly held at *Place René Goblet*, was transferred to *Place Longueville*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] It is a wide esplanade that took the place of the Longueville bastion, after the demolition of the city walls in the early 19th century.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Each year, a temporary circus is established for this occasion.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] In 1865, a circus company emerged to claim a permanent circus, which would be built in wood by the Schytte contractor in 1874.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] However, expensive maintenance prompted the municipality to consider the construction of a new building.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The decision was made in 1886 under the leadership of Mayor Frédéric Petit and the work began.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The Chief Architect of the Somme, Émile Ricquier, a disciple of Gustave Eiffel, was responsible for its construction.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] It was inspired by the Cirque d'hiver of Paris but with a cast metal frame, supplemented by brick from the local countryside.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The architect of civil buildings, Charles Garnier, claimed that the frames should be hidden with a plaster imitating stone.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The "moderninst" design of Ricquier, who chose to display the structure, and to favor local material such as brick, is visible at the rear of the monument.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] With its 16-sided polygonal shape and a diameter of 44 metres (144 ft), it includes lodges and stalls in its enclosure.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] As a completely modern project, it hosted two steam engines, dedicated to fully electric lights and central heating.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Since its construction, it was also the first circus which included a buffet and a refreshment bar.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The cost of the construction of the building finally reached double the forecast.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The roof was damaged by a shell in 1916.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The circus was the setting for Federico Fellini's *The Clowns* (1971), and the film by Jean-Jacques Beineix, *Roselyne and the Lions* (1989), with Isabelle Pasco as lead actress.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The largest of the circuses of the province with its 3,000-seats, the building has acquired a multidisciplinary use for decades of performances of theatre, dance, concerts, galas, sports and public meetings.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Renovated in 2003, it now bears the name of Cirque Jules-Verne.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] After hosting the performances of Cirque Rancy, it hosts resident Cirque Arlette Gruss.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Since 1 January 2011, the circus has been labelled "national hub circus and street arts", managed by an EPCC.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] It is one of seven in France and is still in use today.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] In 1882, Jules Verne and his wife, Honorine, rented the house at the corner of *Rue Charles-Dubois* and *Boulevard Longueville* until 1900.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Acquired in 1980 by the city, the house is labeled Maisons des Illustres by the Ministry of Culture.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Restored in 2006, thanks to the work of the Centre international Jules-Verne, this 19th-century mansion, registered as a national heritage site, traces through the exhibition of more than 700 objects, the personality, the sources of inspiration and memories of Jules Verne.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Opposite the Gare d'Amiens, is located the Tour Perret (from the name of its architect Auguste Perret).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Over 100 metres (330 ft) high, it was one of the first skyscrapers built in Europe, and the highest for a long time.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The Église Saint-Leu d'Amiens was built at the end of the 15th century, on the model of the hall-churches.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] It is dedicated, as its district, to Saint Leu, referring to the 7th century bishop who was exiled to the Vimeu.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] A flamboyant portal adorns the base of the steeple.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The latter, struck by lightning, had to be rebuilt at the beginning of the 16th century.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Stone and wood statues date from the 17th century.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The choir houses the glory of the Duthoit brothers.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Amiens has 270 hectares (670 acres) of green space (excluding communal woodland) 118,300 hectares (292,000 acres) of *hortillonnages*, 300 hectares (740 acres) of forests, 30 hectares (74 acres) of marshland, in addition to its river and its streams.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Floral City awarded the maximum score of 4 flowers in the floral contest of cities and villages of France to Amiens, and it offers a particularly rich wooded heritage.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] With 38,650 trees (excluding woodland), of which 17,000 are situated on highways, Amiens to win the national tree award.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] In 2014, the city ranked in the top 10 greenest cities of France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Presenting itself as a city concerned with the environment, Amiens has made the link between the city and nature a central axis of its metropolitan development project called *Amiens 2030*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Amiens is also known for the hortillonnages, gardens on small islands in over 300 hectares (740 acres) of marshland between the River Somme and River Avre, surrounded by a grid network of human-made canals (locally known as "rieux").
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] They are also known as the "floating gardens of Amiens".
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The *hortillonnages* are sometimes called "Little Venice of the North", because of the canals.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Prior to its opening in May 1952, the Amiens Zoo is a green space bordering the basin of the Park of the Hotoie.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] It was the mayor of the time, Maurice Vast, who decided to develop the site in 1949.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Originally intended as an entertainment venue, the zoo began its mission of conservation, education and research between 1970 and 1980.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Between 1990 and 2000, the zoo was completely renovated and became a permanent member of the European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) in 2001 and the National Association of Zoological Parks (ANPZ) in 2002.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Today, there are 300 animals, representing approximately 75 species from all continents, cohabiting on 6.5 hectares (16 acres).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] They live in environments, which are close to their natural environment, favouring their well-being.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Traditionally, entry is free on 14 July, Bastille Day.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Parc du Grand Marais, along the Somme Canal, to the west of the city.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Covering over 25 hectares (62 acres), this park has many sports facilities: American football stadium, skate bowl, football field, play structures.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Jardin des plantes originally called the *Jardin du Roy*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] Created in 1751, it is the oldest garden of Amiens on the *Boulevard du jardin des plantes*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] As a floral city, 4 flowers were awarded in 2013 by the National Council of Cities and Villages of France for the competition of floral cities and villages.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p03] The national Council of Cities and Villages awarded the 2012 National Tree Prize to the city for "its exceptional and innovative management of its wooded heritage" with its 37,000 trees, some more than a century old.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Amiens was strongly tipped to host the Louvre II.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] The city has a number of concert spaces, mostly small venues, and pubs also host numerous concerts throughout the year.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Amiens Métropole has nine cultural centers which cover much of the metropolitan area: six in various districts of Amiens, and three in the neighbouring communes of Longueau, Camon and Glisy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] These outreach facilities working in the field of art and creation are openly oriented "venues".
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Open to all, they offer an eclectic programme; theatre and concerts, shows for young people and dance, projections of films, exhibitions, meetings and debates.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] The Bibliothèques d'Amiens Métropole is a network of 28 facilities spread over the whole territory of the metropolis.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] The heart of this network is the Louis Aragon library, located on *Rue de la République*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Built between 1823 and 1826, it is one of the oldest municipal libraries in France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] It experienced several improvements, including campaigns of work between 1982 and 1993, which have endowed it with new spaces: Two auditoriums, a youth space, a library and an art library.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Registration and borrowing is free for all of the people of Amiens in all libraries.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Two libraries also provide service to neighborhoods and the communes of the agglomeration, and there is home delivery of documents for people with reduced mobility.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Throughout the year, Amiens is the seat of many cultural, traditional or economic events.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Even if it rarely achieves national notoriety (with the notable exceptions of Les Fatals Picards, The Rabeats, Olympe, Albin de la Simone, Disiz and Rokia Traoré), the Amiens music scene is active and developed.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In this dynamic, the New French Rock scene holds a central place and is organised around a collective, *Amiens Burning*, which is responsible for networking the breeding ground for the local rock scene, to accompany its projects, and organize concerts.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Since their creation, La Lune des Pirates and Cité Carter also provide support to the local scene.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] For example, the Cité Carter produces a compilation each year, with local groups.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Classical music is represented by the Orchestre de Picardie and the University Orchestra of Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Vocal practice is represented by the Regional Choir of Picardy, the University Choir of Picardie, and the Choir of France Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] One can also include the Harmony Saint-Pierre, a fanfare of 70 musicians, which has become a local institution since its inception in 1894.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] The city has the Conservatoire à rayonnement régional d'Amiens, seat of strong musical activity (framed by 70 teachers, an administrative and technical team with an additional 20 people).
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Amiens saw rise, over the centuries, to major writers.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In the first half of the 17th century, Vincent Voiture, poet and letter writer, was the darling of the Précieuses for the fluidity of his style.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In 1634, he was member of the 1st Académie française.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In 1678, Charles du Fresne, sieur du Cange, nicknamed "the French Varro", published his *Glossarium* in 3 volumes.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] This glossary of medieval Latin is still authoritative today.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In 1750, Jean Baptiste Gresset, a playwright and poet who was celebrated in his time and was a member of the Académie française, founded the Academy of Amiens which is still active today.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In 1782, the Amiens native Choderlos de Laclos published *Les Liaisons dangereuses* where he staged a depraved nobility.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Considered one of the masterpieces of 18th-century literature, the book has toured the world and is known as an Oscar-winning film adaptation.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In the 19th century, there was a brilliant literary life around the Académie des sciences, des lettres et des arts d'Amiens with historian Albéric de Calonne and the Yvert family.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] However, the great name of Amiens literary life is Jules Verne.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] He animated all intellectual activity, giving balls and parties, while his wife held a famous salon.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] He often attended the library of the industrial society, which subscribed to numerous scientific journals.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Engaged in local life, he was Councillor of Amiens from 1888 to 1904.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] He was closely interested in the affairs of the city, wrote many reports on the theatre and brought its support to the construction of the municipal circus.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Amiens does appear explicitly in his novels but there are however characteristic elements of the city such as the cathedral and the river.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] This is the case, for example, for the imaginary city of Ragz in *Le secret de Wilhem Storitz*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In the novel *Une fantaisie du docteur Ox*, the inhabitants of the fictional town of Virgamen, the Virgamenois, refer directly to the Amiénois and their prudent nature.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] In 1875, he delivered before the Academy of Sciences, Letters and Arts of Amiens a speech entitled "An ideal city: Amiens in the year 2000" where he portrays himself wandering in a forward-thinking city of Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p04] Since then, the city has built a tourist route from this text.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] He died in Amiens in 1905, and he deeply marked the town's footprint, so that today many places, monuments and events bear his name.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] He rests at La Madeleine cemetery where one can read on his tomb: *Vers l'immortalité et l'éternelle jeunesse.* [Towards immortality and eternal youth].
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] In 1885, Englishman John Ruskin published the Bible of Amiens, which was translated into French, extensively annotated and prefaced, in 1904, by Marcel Proust.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] This book dedicated to Notre-Dame d'Amiens was the opportunity for Proust to recall his admiration for the English author and the Cathedral of Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] In the second half of the 19th century, Jules Barni, Member of Parliament for the Somme, Associate Professor of philosophy and brilliant scholar translated Kant's work in French and thus enabled its dissemination in France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] A native of Amiens, Paul Bourget published *Le Disciple* in 1889, a novel today considered his major work.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] He was elected, 5 years later, to the Académie française.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Born in Sainte-Anne district in 1885, Roland Dorgelès published *Les Croix de bois* in 1919.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] A masterpiece written from his notes taken at the Front, the novel won the Prix Femina the same year.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Though capable of obtaining the Prix Goncourt, it was beaten by À l'ombre des jeunes filles en fleurs by Marcel Proust, 6 votes against 4.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] A member of the Académie Goncourt in 1929, he was elected president in 1954 until his death in 1973.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] In 1926, the Amiens native Henri Deberly, won the Prix Goncourt with Le Supplice de Phèdre, a novel inspired by his home city.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Many films or scenes from films were shot in Amiens and its surroundings.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Amiens is a stronghold of comics in France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] A whole generation of designers and Amiens writers make the city an important creative center of the 9th art.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] The main actors in this generation, include Régis Hautière, Norédine Allam who notably led the recolouring of the 33 Asterix albums in the framework of the project "The great collection" and also Antoine Dodé, David François, Fraco, Hardoc, Greg Blondin, and Nicolas Hitori De.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] The city was also the birthplace or home of big names in the comic strip universe, such as the Amiens native Joseph Pinchon, creator of the character of *Bécassine*; Paul Gillon, winner of the Grand Prix de la ville d'Angoulême and also Philippe Thirault.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Actor of this dynamic around the BD, the association *On a marché sur la bulle* [Explorers on the bubble] organises the Rendez-vous de la bande dessinée d'Amiens, one of the greatest French comic book festivals.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Active throughout the territory, the structure also manages a resource center and has an editorial department with the Éditions de la Gouttière.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Amiens, in the image of the Picardy region, has a rich gastronomic heritage.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] The region is also known for "flamiche aux poireaux", a puff pastry tart made with leeks and cream.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] The Summer Rambo apple cultivar originated near Amiens in the 16th century.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] Marie Denizard (1872-1959), in January 1913, the first woman to stand as a candidate in a French presidential election.
[src:balle-à-la-main/amiens-p05] In 1991, the municipality formed around Gilles de Robien designed a new logo, incorporating the Fleur-de-lis and the Ivy leaf present on the coat of arms, placed side by side in red with a background of grey or white, depending on usage.
[src:balle-à-la-main/aubigny-somme] In Aubigny, teams are playing *balle à la main* which is a traditional sport in Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/balle-à-la-main] The ball is made with a lead pit, surrounded with wool and covered with leather.
[src:balle-à-la-main/balle-à-la-main] The diameter is about 4,2 cm with a weight about 43 g.
[src:balle-à-la-main/balle-à-la-main] The game takes place according to the rules of the games of *gagne-terrain* (gain-ground) with in particular the use of the "*chasses*".
[src:balle-à-la-main/balle-à-la-main] Points for a set count by "fifteen" (15, 30, 45 and set), with possible advantage in the tie-break.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] It is the largest of 47 communes which comprise the Communauté d'agglomération de la Porte du Hainaut, which in 2017 had a total population of 158,754.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] A mere village in the beginning of the 19th century, its population rapidly increased from 1850 until 1962, when it had 29,467 inhabitants.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] Since then its population declined by about 30%.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] Denain was an important centre in the industrial revolution, first for coal-mining from 1720, and steelworks from around 1839.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] The closure of the large Usinor steelworks at Denain was announced in 1978, and the works finally closed in 1988. Émile Zola is thought to have conducted research into the working of the mine and mining communities by visiting Denain before writing Germinal.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] A primary school, a park and a road in Denain bear the name of the novelist.
[src:balle-à-la-main/denain] Former mayor Patrick Roy was also a deputy and became famous for the support for heavy metal music he expressed at the National Assembly on various occasions.
[src:balle-à-la-main/gain-ground] Among these games, longue paume and real tennis are the most well-known because they are played with rackets.
[src:balle-à-la-main/gain-ground] The rules change a little depending on the game, but the basic rules remain identical from one game to the other.
[src:balle-à-la-main/gain-ground] Games of gain-ground are characterized in particular by the use of "*chasses*".
[src:balle-à-la-main/gain-ground] Chasses indicate the limit between both teams or in real tennis a limit to score a point.
[src:balle-à-la-main/gain-ground] Points are counted as in tennis: 15, 30, 40 and set.
[src:balle-à-la-main/longue-paume] It was played as part of the Paris 1900 Summer Olympics, but its medal status is disputed.
[src:balle-à-la-main/longue-paume] Today, the sport is most played in the region of Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/longue-paume] The sport's governing body is the *Fédération Française de Longue Paume*, with its headquarters in Amiens.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Unlike regions such as Normandy, Brittany, or Champagne, Picardy was never established as a duchy, county, or principality.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Its boundaries fluctuated over the centuries due to the political instability in the area it covered.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Since 1 January 2016, it has been part of the new region of Hauts-de-France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The first geographic description of Picardy appeared in the late central Middle Ages, including the bishoprics of Amiens, Beauvais, Arras, Tournai, and Thérouanne.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In the late Middle Ages, it also encompassed Saint-Quentin, Douai, Abbeville, Béthune, Clermont, and other towns such as Noyon, Valenciennes, Boulogne-sur-Mer, Hesdin, and Laon.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] At that time, Picardy was divided into Upper and Lower Picardy: Upper Picardy was closer to Île-de-France, while Lower Picardy, which Barthélemy the Englishman referred to as Hainaut, was closer to Flanders and Brabant.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] During the *ancien régime*, Picardy was generally defined by thirteen traditional regions, still divided into Upper and Lower Picardy: the former grouping inland areas and the latter, coastal areas.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] It was divided between the governments of Picardy and Île-de-France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The government of Picardy covered the northern half of Upper Picardy, while the government of Île-de-France held the southern half, including towns such as Beauvais, Noyon, and Laon.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] This description of Picardy, seen in 19th and 20th-century records from the Society of Antiquaries of Picardy and the Historical Society of Upper Picardy, extended from Senlis to Calais, from Soissons and Laon to Abbeville and Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Historians and geographers such as Robert Fossier, Albert Demangeon, and Philippe Pinchemel replaced the idea of the *ancien régime* Picardy with the notion of an ethnic Picardy, identified particularly by the Picard language.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] This ethnic Picardy would include places like Senlis and Soissons, which popular tradition historically associated with Picardy due to their dialect.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The northern boundary was marked by the linguistic border with Flemish, thus extending to Calais and Tournai.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In the 20th century, geographer Albert Demangeon demonstrated the existence of a geographic Picardy through what he called the "Picard plain", a vast chalk plain stretching from Beauvais to Arras, from Cambrai and Laon to Abbeville and the Boulogne region.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] From 1972 to 2015, a region of the same name was created, bringing together the three departments of Somme, Oise, and Aisne, thus encompassing most of Picardy as defined in the Ancien Régime.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Today, Picardy, in its various definitions, is largely contained within the Hauts-de-France region and comprises five departments.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Part of linguistic Picardy is in the Wallonia region of Belgium, in the Hainaut Province, and a small portion of historic Beauvais is in the northern part of the Val-d'Oise department, around Beaumont-sur-Oise and L'Isle-Adam.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The historical province of Picardy stretched from Senlis to Calais via the main parts of the Oise and Aisne departments, the whole of the Somme department and the west of the Pas-de-Calais department.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The province of Artois (Arras area) separated Picardy from French Flanders.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] From the 5th century, the area formed part of the Frankish Empire and, in the feudal period, it encompassed the six countships of Boulogne, Montreuil, Ponthieu, Amiénois, Vermandois and Laonnois.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In accordance with the provisions of the 843 Treaty of Verdun, the region became part of West Francia, the later Kingdom of France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The name "Picardy" derives from the Old French *pic,* meaning "pike", the characteristic weapon used by people from this region in ancient times.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The term "Picardy" was first used in the early 13th century, during which time the name applied to all lands where the Picard language was spoken including territories from Paris to the Netherlands.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In the Latin Quarter of Paris, people identified a "Picard Nation" (*Nation Picarde*) of students at Sorbonne University, most of whom actually came from Flanders.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] During the Hundred Years' War, Picardy was the centre of the Jacquerie peasant revolt in 1358.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Beginning in 1419, the Picardy counties (Boulogne, Ponthieu, Amiens, Vermandois) were gradually acquired by the Burgundian duke Philip the Good, acquisitions confirmed by King Charles VII of France at the 1435 Congress of Arras.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In 1477, King Louis XI of France led an army and occupied key towns in Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] By the end of 1477, Louis would control all of Picardy and most of Artois.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In the 15th century, the *government* (military region) of Picardy was created.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] This became a new administrative region of France, separate from what was historically defined as Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The new Picardy included the Somme *département*, the northern half of the Aisne *département* and a small fringe in the north of the Oise *département*.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In 1557, Picardy was invaded by Habsburg forces under the command of Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Quentin was ransacked, while Noyon was burned by the Habsburg army.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In the early 18th century, an infectious disease similar to English sweat originated from the region and spread across France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] It was called *Suette des picards* or Picardy sweat.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Sugar beet was introduced by Napoleon I during the Napoleonic Wars in the 19th century in order to counter the United Kingdom which had seized the sugar islands possessed by France in the Caribbean.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The sugar industry has continued to play a prominent role in the economy of the region.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] One of the most significant historical events to occur in Picardy was the series of battles fought along the Somme during World War I.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] From September 1914 to August 1918, four major battles, including the Battle of the Somme, were fought by British, Commonwealth, French and German forces in the fields of Northern Picardy.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] In 2009, the Regional Committee for local government reform proposed to reduce the number of French regions and cancel additions of new regions in the near future.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Picardy would have disappeared and each department would have joined a nearby region.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The Oise would have been incorporated in the Île-de-France, the Somme would have been incorporated in the Nord-Pas-de-Calais and Aisne would have been incorporated in the Champagne-Ardenne.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The vast majority of Picards were opposed to this proposal and it was scrapped in 2010 (see newspaper: "Courrier Picard").
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Today, the modern region of Picardy no longer includes the coastline from Berck to Calais, via Boulogne (Boulonais), that is now in the Nord-Pas-de-Calais region but does incorporate the *pays* of Beauvaisis, Valois, Noyonnais, Laonnois, Soissonnais, Omois among other departments of France.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The older definition of Picardy survives in the name of the Picard language which applies not only to the dialects of Picardy proper but also to the Romance dialects spoken in the Nord-Pas de Calais region, north of Picardy proper, and parts of the Belgian province of Hainaut.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Between the 1990 and 1999 censuses, the population of Oise increased 0.61% per year, almost twice as fast as France as a whole.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Meanwhile the Aisne department lost inhabitants, and the Somme barely grew with a 0.16% growth per year.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Today, 41.3% of the population of Picardy live inside the Oise department.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Picardy stretches from the long sand beaches of the Somme estuary in the west to the vast forests and pastures of the Thiérache in the east to Chantilly and Pierrefonds near the Paris Area and vineyards of the border with Champagne to the south.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The president of the regional council prior to its abolition in 2015 was Claude Gewerc, a Socialist who had been in office since 2004.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] That year he defeated longtime UDF incumbent Gilles de Robien.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Since 2008, the mayor of the city of Amiens, the regional capital, has been Socialist Gilles Demailly.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] He defeated longtime mayor Gilles de Robien of the New Centre party.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Historically, the region of Picardy has a strong and proud cultural identity.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The villages of Picardy have a distinct character, with their houses made of red bricks, often accented with a "lace" of white bricks.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] A minority of people still speak the Picard language, one of the languages of France, which is also spoken in Artois (Nord-Pas de Calais *région*).
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] "P'tit quinquin", a Picard song, is a symbol of the local culture (and of that of Artois).
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Picardy is arguably the birthplace of Gothic architecture, housing six of the world's greatest examples of Gothic cathedrals, which span the history of Gothic architecture in its entirety.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Amiens Cathedral, standing as the largest cathedral in Europe, which according to John Ruskin is the "Pantheon of Gothic architecture", could house Notre-Dame de Paris twice over.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] Picardy also holds the tallest transept in the history of the Gothic period; this transept is located in Saint-Pierre cathedral in Beauvais, Oise.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The Museum of Picardy in Amiens, built between 1855 and 1867, houses a vast array of great works, spanning the centuries and ranging from archaeology from ancient Greece and Egypt to modern works of Pablo Picasso.
[src:balle-à-la-main/picardy] The museum was closed until the end of 2019 for building work.
